column45: Other, Change the date when order is due.
column49: It is not wise for Scholastic to not let you change the date. I usually do monthly orders. Now instead of getting two orders from me, you get one. You lose money and I can't earn as many points.  Plus - I usually give two weeks for orders to be due.  That way parents can budget with a bi-weekly paycheck. Now everyone will just forget about Scholastic because you are giving them 49 days to place their order. 49 days?!?!?!? So I have one parent who just submitted their order. To get the most points I can I need to wait until October 11th to submit that order.  That kiddo has to wait well over a month to get his books. Is that really your intent or am I missing something?

column7: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/115.0.0.0 Safari/537.36
column49: I have been a teacher for 18 years. I have been a LOYAL Scholastic customer and spent many hours emailing parents about the benefit of ordering books., how it helped our classroom. Entering book orders, unpacking and delivering orders to kids...It was ALWAYS worth it when I earned 10k bonus points to start the year off....But that is now gone. I also always ordered the birthday coupons for my 1st grades. Those are gone. My families placed over $600 in book orders this month and I only get 4k bonus points.....it used to be spend $200 and get $10k bonus points, then it became spend $300 for the 10k....and now even when my parents spend TWICE that, I get less than HALF the points I did for the last 18 years. Unfortunately....all this work is not being rewarded enough for me to validate the amount of time I spend on Scholastic Book club. I plan to use up my points this year and then say goodbye to Scholastic Book Club. It was a good run I suppose.

column49: Hi,  The new system for ordering books makes it difficult for my student's parents to use. I would like an order form that has the tax included that I can send home and they can return to the teacher. The new order forms rely on the parents being able to use the q-r code. In the community that I teach, parents need flyers that are simple to use. They are not used to using those types of codes to order items. Many of the items are $___.99 which means that families have to calculate their own taxes or they will turn in order forms that have $.99 in cash which makes it more likely that the teacher will have to pay the taxes out of her own pocket. I would like to return to the same flyer system that you had in previous years. I'm not sure I will be ordering any books with this new system.

column49: I have been a customer for over 25 years.  I'm so disappointed with the new Bonus Point offerings.  As you can see, I've submitted an order over $500.00.  Put the electronic options back in your bonus catalog.  I want the Apple Watch.  It's a ton of work to enter these student orders and to get them their books.  The needed bonus points has increased tremendously this year and the way to earn them has gone down tremendously.  I said I would never order from Scholastic again, but accidentally left the link up so my pre-teachers started ordering and "boom" now I have an order well over $525.00.  Again, please put some goodies back for us teachers who get you the business.  Sincerely, Angela Thomas, AngThom@bgsu.edu

column49: I have to say I am overwhelmingly disappointed in what I am seeing this year.  I have been sharing your flyers with my students for 29 years!!  This year only 5,000 bonus points with a $200 order...what happened to the 10,000??  My first order of the year is ALWAYS my biggest and look forward to collecting these points for resources for my class.  VERY DISAPPOINTED!!  Also, where are the $1.00 books?  I always use my $10 credit to buy 10 books to give back to my students for Christmas presents.  Now, the cheapest you offer is $3.00...again VERY DISAPPOINTED!!!!  Now I can only get 3 books to give back.  You may have just lost a longtime customer.  I'm hoping you make changes back to the benefits that teachers received.  Passing out the flyers, keeping up with the money, and answering parent questions in regards to book orders is very time consuming.  You need to give teachers the better incentives since we are promoting your company.

column49: I don’t like not being able to pick my due date.  When a co teacher called she was told just tell parents a due date you want.  So we did that.  But now when they go on the site you will have a whole month later listed as the due date.      You may think you are helping us by setting our due date but you are not.      Plus you didn’t bother to tell us this info in a timely fashion so I personally spent over 15 min on the site trying to find where you might have moved this feature or if I had missed something to set the darn due date.  Not cool!      I appreciate you trying to save us time but we all have different ways of doing things and different reasons for our due dates.  If we tell parents a due date and they log in and see something different that isn’t helpful and sends a mixed message and makes it look like we are disorganized. I tried to “find my teacher” as I would if I was a parent.  I found our small preschool without any trouble, but I’m not listed as the teacher who does the ordering.  The two people listed are a parent who mistakingly set up a teacher account 10 years ago, and my co teacher who also mistakingly set up an account last year while she was trying to shop as a parent.    I also had a hard time finding the Bonus Point Catalog, now changed to “The Points Shop”.

column49: Will teachers ever be able to enter their own order due date?  There is such a big window for order placement to be open and a parent who places an order right way will have to wait 3 more weeks until their order is submitted, not to mention delivery time on top of that. It was much more user friendly when teachers could set their own order due dates rather than having Scholastic set an arbitrary date.  Why did this change? Also, some families would rather send a check or cash to school rather than ordering online.  Our school is over 80% poverty, so many parents don't use credit or debit.

column49: The site works well, but my biggest complaint is the price of the books this year.   What happened to the dollar deals?!?  I've done the scholastic book fairies for the last 3 years now and I've been able to create amazing libraries for each of my students.  This year I've received the biggest donation yet, but I don't think I'll be able to give this group anywhere near the number of books as I have in the past due to the high cost of your books this year.  I've given my kiddos "I know an old lady who swallowed a birthday cake" for their birthday book, but this year I can't afford to do that because you have it so incredibly overpriced this year.  I'm sad to say that if your prices don't come down asap, I will not be using Scholastic next year at all.

column49: I do not like your new format of online ordering for parents. I teach in an urban school system with a high poverty rate and a large immigrant/non-English speaking population. Your change in policy reflects a privileged outlook on life assuming all people have access to the internet and/or credit/debit cards. My students would bring me the money in/cash because that is how lower income people  conduct business. I would then submit the order and they would get their books a few weeks later. You are now expecting people to create accounts, find the school, their teacher, and then pay with a bank card.     Your change in policy angers me and I am disappointed in your lack of sensitivity to the members of our community/nation who don't have access.

column49: The change to only accept student orders online is a change for the worse in high-poverty districts like mine. Many of my students' families are unbanked and do not have credit cards or sometimes even bank accounts. They still operate using cash. Sometimes, my middle school students would save up their extra allowance to buy a book for themselves or as a present for a sibling or a friend. Since tax isn't calculated until the order is in the system, I would have to pay the added tax myself on any cash orders I take in.  This is really disappointing. I've been a Scholastic teacher for 12 years, and it's just become less accessible to the students who need it most. Please rethink this change.

column49: I teach Spanish to English-speaking elementary kids. I would like to see books aimed at this market. Many times, books translated straight into Spanish are too difficult for students who have the interests of older kids, but the reading abilities of younger. In other words, it needs to be comprehensible to emerging readers without being too childish. Graphic novels in Spanish with easy to find glossaries would be a great fit for this demographic!

column49: I am frustrated with your selection of books. For years I have given my students a book a month. Like so many fellow teachers, it is becoming more and more difficult to provide this. I am a veteran teacher who raises a good deal of money each summer and yet, it isn't enough. As of right now, I cannot even find a $2 book. I could afford that. However, I have gotten NUMEROUS emails from you encouraging me to raise funds to do just that. It is beyond frustrating. column49: I work with low income families in a school that is over 80% English Language Learners. This demographic does not typically have bank accounts and a way to shop online. The parents of these students do not speak or read English. These families rely on the teachers ordering their students the book. They give the cash to the students who then bring it to the teacher and enter it into the system. I now have to create and keep a list of what students bought what book. I feel that this is a serious disadvantage to the students who are already disadvantaged. I really hope scholastic seriously reconsiders the new way they are making families do it all online. Going back to the old order form and having it be an option for teachers to enter in students book would be best.

column49: Very disappointed to see that now the only option for parents to order is online. Not all families in my area are able to have internet. This causes a difficult challenge for some families, which limits equal access to books. I am also not allowed to provide email addresses of my families. This is confidential information.  I have used Scholastic book club orders for 35 years. Very disappointed that the students are not able to return a paper order to the teacher. I have some families with non-literate parents. This has always been a priority of mine to help students have access to books in their homes. Now it's a challenge or impossible for those students who need it the most. Giving parents the choice of an online order OR a paper order was simple and easy to manage. Now I am unsure how often I will use your company.

column49: I was disappointed to see the weekly $1 book of the week gone. The $2 book of the month is great but as a Head Start teacher this option is not as great. I would like to see the 10 pack book bundles back for $10. I understand prices go up but it was a shocking surprise to see everything I loved is gone. I am sad to say I will probably be looking elsewhere for more options for affordable pre-k and kindergarten level books. Sometimes I get donations for friends to purchase books for my class. It’s easier requesting smaller amounts for donation but I was sad to see the prices went up this year and what I had planned to spend is not happening. I love scholastic but I don’t think this will be my go to book shop anymore.
